<div class="heading">Description</div>
'''Object 38''', known as '''Doom Locks''', are electronic keypad-based door locks found in slightly treacherous hallway-like levels of the Backrooms, including, but not limited to, [[Level 21]], [[Level 26]], and [[Level 42]]. The lock's keypad is at the top of the device, with the doorknob in the middle, and a hidden screen is at the bottom. Once a wanderer interacts with the keypad or doorknob, the lock's bottom screen displays the 1993 game Doom, with a small speaker for playing the game's audio. Once the wanderer finishes the game, the door unlocks. The door then leads wanderers to random levels, usually safe havens such as [[Level 330]], [[Level 399]], [[Level 98]], and many others.

Finding '''Doom Locks''' is notably challenging, even in levels where it manifests. Assuming wanderers are in the desired level and travel nonstop while never reentering previously visited areas<ref>This only includes levels unaffected by non-Euclidean phenomena.</ref>, wanderers would take approximately three to seven days to find a '''Doom Lock'''.<ref>The time estimate given does not account for any breaks the wanderer may take in-between travels.</ref> In levels unaffected by Phenomenon 15, instances of '''Doom Locks''' are visible to only one wanderer unless interacted with. Once the lock unlocks and the wanderer enters through the door, it will manifest for another wanderer, and the lock will not be visible or usable to the previous individual who used it. 

In the [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]], it would take an average person 5 hours to beat Classic Doom. However, four leading factors increase the average time needed to finish the version in '''Doom Locks'''. Firstly, the wanderer has to crouch slightly to see the bottom screen, increasing discomfort and possibly causing spinal issues. Secondly, one must use the keypad to control the player character in the game, which would take ample time to adapt to, especially in the position mentioned earlier. Thirdly, the screen is too diminutive for a wanderer to process thoroughly, which causes many failures in runs, further driving up playtime. Lastly, most wanderers are unfamiliar with playing first-person shooters, notably Classic Doom. These factors drive up the time to unlock a '''Doom Lock''' to an average of 9 hours.

In addition, the audio emanating from a '''Doom Lock''' and the wanderer standing still defenseless increases their susceptibility to hostile entities. Standing still for nine hours depletes a wanderer's resources, mainly sustenance. If the '''Doom Lock'''<nowiki/>'s keypad remains untouched for five minutes, it will reset to the beginning, giving wanderers a small window to perform other actions. For every reset, the game's difficulty, which starts at "Hey, not too rough,"<ref>"Hey, not too rough" is Classic Doom's second easiest difficulty setting.</ref> increases, and the subsequent window's time is reduced by 30 seconds. The lock has a maximum of three resets, and the '''Doom Lock''' bricks<ref>[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brick_(electronics) Bricking]</ref> when reaching the 4th reset.

'''Doom Locks''' are indestructible, and so are their respective doors. In addition, attempting to interfere with the lock's software through any means results in the bricking of any involved devices, including the lock itself. Attempting to toy with a lock while another wanderer is using it will also result in its bricking. Bricked '''Doom Locks''' vanish when the wanderer looks away for five seconds. Opening a door that had a bricked lock sends one to [[The Void]], or in semi-rare instances, [[The Broken]].

The discovery of '''Doom Locks''' dates back to July 5, 2020, when some wanderers in [[Level 42]] reported hearing faint noises of the song ''At Doom's Gate'', the most popular OST for the game Doom. A few days later, wanderers found the first lock in the level. It was not until July 31, 2020, when the first '''Doom Lock''' was unlocked, which led the individual to [[Level 399]]. Rumors about the object leading wanderers to safe havens spread rapidly, and many wanderers wanted to attempt unlocking it, with many ending in failure. Today, '''Doom Locks''' are an infamous method to potentially access safe havens, although not recommended by masses due to the many dangers.

